# Final Robot Setup Manual

## 1. Repository Structure

```text
├── final.ino                   # Main Arduino deployment script
│   └── secrets.h               # Network and MQTT credentials configuration
├── README.md                   # Setup and documentation manual
├── software_overview_diagram   # Software architecture diagram
├── flowcharts                  # Robot decision-flow diagrams
└── calibration_evidence        # Sensor, motor, IMU, and field-test evidence
```

Current development note: this repository is still maintained in PlatformIO as
`src/main.cpp`. For final Arduino IDE submission, copy the validated deployment
code into `final.ino` and keep `secrets.h` in the same sketch folder.

## 2. Required Libraries

Before compiling the code, open Arduino IDE Library Manager and install the
following dependencies:

- `MiniMessenger` - Official challenge communication library.
- `ArduinoMqttClient` - Core dependency required by MiniMessenger.
- `Motoron` - Official Pololu library for controlling the N20 dual motor shields.
- `ICM_20948` - SparkFun library for handling the 9-DOF IMU gyroscope tracking.
- `MFRC522_I2C` - Library for reading grid checkpoint RFID cards over the I2C bus.
- `Servo` - Standard Arduino library used to control the 360-degree continuous rotation micro servo.
- `Wire` and `Arduino` - Built-in core frameworks for standard I2C communication and Arduino GIGA pin mappings.

## 3. Setup Steps

### Step 1: Configure Your Secrets File

Create a new tab in the Arduino IDE named `secrets.h` inside the final robot
sketch folder. Copy and paste the lab network credentials below:

```cpp
#define WIFI_SSID "PhaseSpaceNetwork_2.4G"
#define WIFI_PASSWORD "8igMacNet"
#define BROKER_HOST "192.168.0.74"
#define BROKER_PORT 1883
#define GROUP_ID "5"
#define BOARD_ID "Thomas"
```

`BOARD_ID` should be short and contain no spaces. If the team changes the robot
name, update only this field.

### Step 2: Hardware Interfacing Checklist

Ensure all onboard modules are correctly connected to the Arduino GIGA R1.

#### Motoron Shields

- I2C SDA -> `SDA1`
- I2C SCL -> `SCL1`
- Lower Motoron address: `0x10`
- Upper Motoron address: `0x11`
- Lower Motoron M1 -> RF motor
- Lower Motoron M2 -> RR motor
- Lower Motoron M3 -> LR motor
- Upper Motoron M1 -> LF motor

#### RFID Sensor

- VCC -> `5V`
- GND -> `GND`
- SDA -> `SDA1`
- SCL -> `SCL1`
- I2C address: `0x28`
- Reset pin: not connected; the code uses software reset.

#### Reflectance Sensor Array

- VCC -> `3.3V`
- GND -> `GND`
- Out 1 -> `D22`
- Out 2 -> `D23`
- Out 3 -> `D24`
- Out 4 -> `D25`
- Out 5 -> `D26`
- Out 6 -> `D27`
- Out 7 -> `D28`
- Out 8 -> `D30`
- Out 9 -> `D31`

The line-following logic uses Out 1/3/5/7/9 as the main five logical points:
right, slight-right, middle, slight-left, and left. Out 2/4/6/8 are available
for debugging and future stability improvements.

#### Ultrasonic Sensors

- VCC -> `5V`
- GND -> `GND`
- Front Echo -> `D37`
- Front Trig -> `D39`
- Left Echo -> `D52`
- Left Trig -> `D44`
- Right Echo -> `D46`
- Right Trig -> `D48`

Do not use `D31` for ultrasonic triggering, because `D31` is assigned to
reflectance sensor Out 9.

#### Revive Button

- One side -> `GND`
- Other side -> `D32`

#### Mechanical Kill Switch Button

- One side -> `GND`
- Other side -> `D45`

#### Status LEDs

- Red LED -> `D36`
- Green LED -> `D38`

#### Servo Motor

- Signal -> `D10`
- VCC -> `5V`
- GND -> `GND`

Servo signal was moved from `D7` to `D10` because `D6` and `D7` are difficult
to access and are also kept available for encoder-related wiring.

## 4. How to Upload and Run the Code

### Uploading to the Board

- Connect the Arduino GIGA R1 WiFi to the computer using a reliable USB-C cable.
- In the Arduino IDE, go to `Tools -> Board` and select:
  `Arduino Mbed OS GIGA Boards -> Arduino GIGA R1`.
- Go to `Tools -> Port` and select the active COM port assigned to the GIGA.
- Click the Verify checkmark button to compile.
- Click Upload to flash the code to the robot.
- Open Serial Monitor at `115200` baud.

For PlatformIO development, the equivalent upload command is:

```bash
/Users/admin/.platformio/penv/bin/platformio run --target upload
```

The serial monitor command is:

```bash
/Users/admin/.platformio/penv/bin/platformio device monitor -e giga_r1_m7 --port /dev/cu.usbmodem101 --baud 115200
```

### Running and Testing the Kill Switch

- Connect the laptop or debugging device to the lab network:
  `PhaseSpaceNetwork_2.4G`.
- Open the team dashboard:
  `http://192.168.0.74:8090/team/5`
- Use the dashboard Enable/Disable buttons to test remote safety stop.
- The robot must continuously call `messenger.loop()` inside the main loop so
  MiniMessenger can intercept emergency payloads.
- On emergency disable, the robot should call `stopAllMotors()` immediately.

Mechanical kill switch testing:

- Press the D45 kill button once to stop the robot.
- Press D45 again to allow movement.
- When stopped, the red LED should blink.
- The D32 revive button controls the green LED indication.

Expected serial messages:

```text
KILL | Mechanical D45 -> STOP
KILL | Mechanical D45 -> RUN
RFID | Card ID: ...
```

## 5. Current Development Notes

- Current development code may still use `src/main.cpp`; final deployment should
  be consolidated into `final.ino`.
- If RFID-only testing is enabled with `RFID_ONLY_TEST = true`, the robot will
  not run motors or line following. Set it to `false` before a full robot run.
- Reflectance sensor Out 9 is connected to `D31`.
- Servo signal should use `D10`.
- MiniMessenger/MQTT is required for the final remote kill switch behaviour.
